        <h2 id="examples">Real link bait examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Accounting firm annual data report</h3>
        <p>An accounting firm published an annual "Small Business Tax Deductions Most People Miss" report based on a survey of 500 business owners. The report combined proprietary survey data with a fresh annual publication cadence — meaning every year, new writers covering tax topics had a fresh dataset to cite. Year one: 89 referring domains. By year three: 230+. Zero ongoing link outreach after initial publication.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS free tool with supporting content</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company published a free website grading tool on its blog. The tool generated a shareable score report, giving users a reason to embed or link to it. The company built 30 supporting blog posts internally linking to the tool, boosting its topical authority. Review sites, agency resource pages, and competitor comparisons all started linking to the tool as a neutral reference. The tool now drives more organic traffic than any single blog post on the site.</p>

        <h3>3. Industry myth-busting study</h3>
        <p>An email marketing platform published "The Email Open Rate Lie: Why Your Numbers Are Wrong" with data showing that Apple Mail Privacy Protection had made open rates inaccurate for 40% of recipients. The contrarian angle — challenging a metric the entire industry relied on — generated coverage from marketing news sites, podcast citations, and LinkedIn discussion. 140+ referring domains in the first three months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Link bait vs clickbait — key difference</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Link bait</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Delivers genuine value to the reader</li>
              <li>Earns links because content is trustworthy and useful</li>
              <li>Builds domain authority and brand reputation</li>
              <li>Links are editorial — given voluntarily by other writers</li>
              <li>Compounds over time as more writers discover it</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Clickbait</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Uses misleading headlines to get clicks</li>
              <li>Rarely earns real editorial links — generates traffic not trust</li>
              <li>Damages brand credibility when content disappoints</li>
              <li>Short shelf life — curiosity clicks don't repeat</li>
              <li>Associated with Google's quality penalties</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for creating link bait</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with proprietary data.</strong> The single most reliable link bait format is a stat nobody else has. Run a survey (SurveyMonkey, Typeform) targeting your audience. Even 200 responses on a specific niche question produces citable data.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the format to your network.</strong> If your niche is visual (design, data), infographics and interactive tools earn links faster. If it is textual and research-heavy (law, finance, healthcare), comprehensive guides and studies outperform visuals.</li>
          <li><strong>Plan for the second wave.</strong> Publish the core asset, then create 5-10 supporting blog posts internally linking to it. This builds topical authority signals that help the link bait page rank for the queries it targets, making it discoverable by more potential linkers.</li>
          <li><strong>Seed the first 30 days actively.</strong> Link bait earns passively over time, but it needs initial visibility. Identify 20-30 journalists, bloggers, or newsletter writers who cover your topic and send a brief, personalised note with the data. This first wave of links creates the social proof that triggers organic discovery.</li>
          <li><strong>Update annually for data assets.</strong> A "State of X in 2024" report stops being cited when it becomes outdated. Annual updates reset the publication date, give you a PR hook for re-promotion, and retain existing links while earning new ones.</li>
          <li><strong>Make data embeddable.</strong> Charts, infographics, and interactive elements with embed codes generate links automatically. Every site that embeds your chart links back to the source — attribution is built into the format.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — trying to make everything link bait</div>
          <p>Not every piece of content should be link bait. How-to posts, service pages, and category content serve different purposes. Attempting to engineer every post for link earning produces content that is too broad to rank and too shallow to earn links. Reserve link bait investment for 2-4 cornerstone pieces per year that anchor your topical cluster.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common link bait mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Publishing data without a unique angle.</strong> "Our survey found most marketers use email" is not citable because it confirms what everyone already knows. Citable data surprises, challenges, or quantifies something previously unmeasured.</li>
          <li><strong>No promotion for the first 30-90 days.</strong> Passive link earning requires initial visibility. Without seeding, excellent content can sit unnoticed for months.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating link bait disconnected from your site's topic.</strong> A viral piece that earns links from unrelated domains provides almost no topical authority benefit. The best link bait earns links from within your content niche.</li>
          <li><strong>Outdated data left in place without update notice.</strong> A 2023 study with no update notice actively harms your credibility when readers notice the data is stale. Either update annually or add a clear "last updated" date and note the limitations.</li>
          <li><strong>Mistaking traffic for links.</strong> Viral content gets traffic. Link bait earns links. A piece can get 50,000 social shares and zero editorial backlinks if nothing in it is citable. Shares and links require different content properties.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is link bait the same as clickbait?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Clickbait uses misleading headlines to get clicks without delivering value. Link bait delivers genuine value that makes other site owners want to reference it. The distinction is substance: link bait earns links because it is genuinely useful; clickbait earns clicks but not editorial citations or lasting SEO value.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
